##Expert replays: "unexplained pneumonia" reported behind the failure

It's all in the paper

How do we turn this into a containment operation in time?

On the afternoon of February 6, a vehicle carrying medical equipment and staff arrived at Huoshenshan Hospital in Wuhan. Photograph: Chen Zhuo for Changjiang daily

On the evening of January 8, Zeng Guang, the chief epidemiologist of the Chinese Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) , was suddenly notified by the National Health and Safety Commission that he should go to Wuhan as soon as possible. The next morning, at 7 a.m. , he boarded a flight from Beijing to Wuhan.

Having spent only one day in Wuhan, Zeng did not take part in the on-site investigation. In local reports to experts, including himself, he heard how many people had been quarantined in Wuhan, no one in close contact had been infected, and the patients were not too ill, similar to seasonal flu... "that's all we got, " Zeng said, patting his desk as he recalled the experience to China Newsweek. "How did I know there was a Li Wenliang and a Zhang Jixian? "

Even on the basis of this information, Zeng, based on his experience during the SARS period, advised the local authorities to isolate the infected people completely. Suspected patients should not only be admitted to the hospital, but also each person should be given a single room, and close contacts should be isolated centrally, this is the point of prevention and control. But at the time, Wuhan did not adopt such measures.

"It's an extra burden on them. "

When Zeng went to Wuhan, the National Health Commission also sent a second group of experts to Han on January 8 to conduct local investigation and guide the epidemic prevention work until January 15.

A member of the group told China Newsweek that at the time, the information available to the group was limited and it was difficult to determine whether the virus was capable of human-to-human transmission. He recalled that on January 11, when the Hubei and Wuhan Health Committees met with an expert group from the National Health Commission, they provided a list of suspected cases with more than 100 people. The consensus of the panel is to report suspected cases truthfully. But on the 12th, the Wuhan Municipal Health Commission's report repeated only the previous day's report of 41 confirmed cases, and did not disclose suspected cases. The panel was surprised by this.

The clinician is infected, is the patient-to-patient sensitive signal. According to later media reports, from January 1 to 11, seven medical staff in Wuhan have been infected. Among them, Wuhan Tongji Hospital Doctor Lu Jun was diagnosed with new coronary pneumonia on January 7, in January 17, has been treated in the hospital. At the time, the experts said, they also visited Tongji in Wuhan, but no one told them about the infection among the hospital's medical staff.

On Feb. 23, Chen Guoqiang, an academician of the Chinese Academy of Sciences and President of the School of Medicine, Shanghai Jiao Tong University, and others published a commentary in the Journal of Chinese Science: Life Sciences, entitled thinking under the COVID-19 infection. The article pointed out that in the early days of the outbreak, clinicians had already felt the seriousness of the problem and the possibility of human-to-human transmission from case to case, but no professional and efficient public health team could reach the scene at the first time, conduct detailed and rigorous epidemiological investigations and timely diagnosis of problems.

Many people are questioning why the national direct reporting system for infectious diseases established after SARS did not work. "In fact, the direct reporting system is not responsible for finding Emerging Infectious Diseases, " Wang Hua, president of the Jiangsu Preventive Medicine Association and former Director of the Jiangsu Provincial Center for Disease Control and Prevention and deputy director of the provincial health department, told China Newsweek

In response to the Emerging Infectious Diseases, the Infectious Disease Prevention Act was amended in December 2004 to include in the list of infectious diseases to be reported, added "or the discovery of other infectious disease outbreaks, epidemics, and outbreaks of infectious disease of unknown cause" . The Emerging Infectious Diseases can be reported through the public health emergency reporting system, a subsystem of the direct reporting system. But the problem is that it can only be reported if it first defines what constitutes a public health event.

In response, Li Liming, a professor at Peking University's Public Health and the first director of the National CDC, pointed out that the Revised Law on the prevention and control of infectious diseases has only one sentence for these Emerging Infectious Diseases, "That is to say to report, but how to report no clear rules. " So, January 20, the state regulation of new CORONAVIRUS PNEUMONIA AS "B type infectious disease, according to the management of a" , every day began to report. "until now, there has been no identification of what the disease is, how harmful it is, and the process of expert evaluation and decision-making by the health administration, " said Li Liming, according to the National CDC website, the infectious disease direct online reporting system for the Official infectious was launched on January 24,2020.

Chen Guoqiang and others pointed out that as early as 2011, experts from China's CDC and the U.S. CDC had already written an article that, while summarizing the achievements made in capacity building of the Emerging Infectious Diseases since SARS in 2003, it also points to a significant gap in China's Emerging Infectious Diseases capabilities.

In fact, at present, China's Disease Control System, can monitor infectious diseases is not only a direct reporting system. Since 2004, the former Ministry of Health has required nationwide surveillance of cases of pneumonia of unknown cause (Pue) , a separate system. Pue Is linked to the direct reporting system for infectious diseases. That is, doctors can report cases of pneumonia of unknown cause through the direct reporting system via PUE.

Pue Is a passive surveillance system that relies on medical institutions' clinicians to report cases, according to a 2017 master's thesis "evaluation of surveillance systems for pneumonia of unknown cause, " directed by Feng Zijian, deputy director of the National CDC, the acceptance of the monitoring system by clinicians has a direct impact on the quality and efficiency of case reporting. In 2013, the vast majority of human cases of H7N9 in Jiangsu and Anhui were detected through PUE. However, the paper points out that there are currently a large number of cases in hospitals that meet the definition of Pue, but the reporting rate is low.

On December 29,2019, local hospitals in Wuhan detected the first four reported cases of new coronavirus pneumonia through the PUE surveillance system, according to an article published Jan. 29 in the Journal The New England Journal of Medicine by the State and Hubei Provincial CDC. In fact, according to a retrospective analysis by the Chinese CDC, 104 people had been infected and 15 had died by Dec. 31,2019, based on the date of onset.

"when the clinician sees a patient with pneumonia of unknown cause, he is required to report it immediately, but in practice no one cares. Doctors are very busy, and reporting it means a lot of follow-up registration and investigation work, which is an extra burden for them,"Wang said, at present, fever clinics, unexplained pneumonia surveillance systems, influenza surveillance systems, are independent of each other, because of the management of different departments, scattered in the management of individual medical institutions.

In response, several public health experts said that these decentralized monitoring systems should be combined to establish a unified respiratory disease monitoring system, while at the same time opening up the clinical diagnosis, reporting, treatment and epidemic prevention and control links. For example, could you make an improvement in the hospital's electronic diagnosis and treatment system, so that when a doctor sees a patient with pneumonia of unknown origin, without filling out a separate form, just click a button in his system, and the case can be sent to the monitoring system.

In this outbreak, many clinicians in the early detection of abnormalities, but due to the lack of a clear diagnosis, direct reporting system can not be used, only layers of manual reporting. On December 28,2019, her emergency department received four fever cases related to the south China Seafood Market, the head of the Emergency Department at Wuhan Central Hospital, Ai Fen, told China News Weekly, it was reported to the hospital's Public Health Department on the 29th. The hospital's Public Health Department reported it to the Kong HON CDC in Wuhan. The Chinese and Western Medicine Hospital of Hubei Province and the Wuhan Red Cross Hospital had previously reported similar cases, the reply said.

According to media reports, near the south China Seafood Market, a second-level hospital called Youfu received more than cases of fever of unknown origin. Around January 10, although the hospital will focus on fever reported to the Higher CDC Department, but the other side did not immediately come to the hospital for research. In response, Tang Jinling, emeritus professor of epidemiology at the Chinese University of Hong Kong, pointed out that the judgment of front-line clinicians should be valued. In future improvements to surveillance systems, consideration should be given to incorporating the observations and judgments of clinicians.

Regarding the relationship between clinicians and disease control experts in the early days of an epidemic, Li Liming said that the emergency departments of every hospital in the United States have CDC experts assigned to their tasks, is in the emergency room at any time to find new abnormal cases, to establish a highly sensitive epidemic surveillance system. A disease control specialist working with a clinician is a true combination of medicine and prevention.

Epidemiology is the basic professional support for disease prevention and control, including disease surveillance, outbreak reporting, on-site investigation and public health decision-making, Zeng said. Zeng sees epidemiology as "intelligence work" . Now, however, he feels that communication channels between professionals and policymakers are not yet open and that public health information is difficult to translate into timely and effective decision-making. Many experts point out that there is still much room for improvement in the operational aspects of monitoring and locating the source of infection in the early stages of the epidemic.

Late at night on February 18, Chen Lei, a dispatcher at Wuhan Emergency Center, was at work. Since the outbreak of new crown pneumonia, the workload of the Wuhan Emergency Center has increased dramatically, and Chen Lei works nonstop from 8 pm to 8 am every day. One of her wishes was, "when this epidemic is over, I'm going to get a good night's sleep! " Photograph: Changjiang Daily, Chen Liang

"better to kill a thousand than miss one. "

"when the abnormality is detected, the next step is to make the right diagnosis. Instead of waiting for a diagnosis at an early stage of a new disease, we should take timely social action based on symptoms,"said Jiang Qingwu, a professor of epidemiology and former dean of the public health at the Fudan University.

According to Caixin Media, during a training session for local doctors on Jan. 4, the Wuhan Municipal Commission of Health and Human Services issued the viral pneumonia for unknown causes (trial) and the criteria for viral pneumonia for unknown causes. Among them, the former was developed by the first group of experts of the Health Commission and the local experts of Hubei, and the "standards for entering the row" was compiled by the Health Commission of Wuhan.

In contrast, the criteria compiled by Wuhan Municipal Commission of Health and hygiene are more stringent in terms of diagnostic criteria, with a history of clinical presentation and Epidemiology, i. e. a history of exposure to the south China seafood market. However, many retrospective studies have shown that overemphasis on the epidemiological characteristics of "market exposure history of seafood in south China" will miss many cases. For example, according to a paper published in the Lancet by Huang Chaolin, vice president of Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital, 14 of the original 41 cases of pneumonia of unknown cause in the hospital had no history of exposure to the south China seafood market. A Jan. 29 article in the The New England Journal of Medicine by Takatomi, director of the National CDC, and others, also showed that only 55 percent of cases that occurred before Jan. 1 were related to the south China Seafood Market.

In response, Zhang Dingyu, director of Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital, told China News weekly that in the early days of the epidemic, experts would take the history of contact with the south China seafood market as a very important basis in the epidemiological sense, "No one can say what it is based on a CT scan or a blood test. Now, as long as radiologists get CT scans and add patients'symptoms, such as more coughing and less expectoration, they dare to pat their chest and say that it is new coronary pneumonia,"several experts have also pointed out, the outbreak of the new coronavirus, which coincides with the influenza and Atypical pneumonia epidemic season and also with a high incidence of respiratory infections, makes the differential diagnosis of a new respiratory infection more difficult.

But Li Liming pointed out that the case screening criteria are strict, the benefits of more accurate grasp, but in fact it is very dangerous to do so. "In order to find and control the source of infection, 'better to kill a thousand than to miss one' is the principle, so it is important to emphasize that the diagnostic methods should be more sensitive and that the clinical diagnostic criteria should probably be wider to ensure that no suspicious source of infection is missed. ".

Feng Zijian, deputy director of the National CDC, later admitted to the media that he had a conservative tendency to judge the outbreak because of a bias toward more accurate case locking. "The difficulty in this process is that there is no diagnostic reagent, and when the reagent is available, early indications also indicate that the positive rate of the reagent for Upper and lower respiratory tract specimens is relatively low at the beginning of use, and we dare not easily rule it out. Given this early limitation, we are very cautious in our conclusions."

Since the outbreak of the epidemic more than a month ago, the NCP has been revised five times and produced six versions because the presence of the pathogen has been confirmed, these protocols require that one of the conditions for the diagnosis of NCP is a positive test for the pathogen.

According to Hu Shanlian, a professor of public health at Fudan University, nucleic acid tests are needed to identify patients, and the initial lack of nucleic acid test kits has caused some delay in the prevention and control of the epidemic. "Some of the suspected patients should have been confirmed eventually, " he said. "Many of the suspected patients were not diagnosed in time due to insufficient supplies of test kits, which also contributed to transmission. "

Chen Guoqiang and others also pointed out that since the outbreak of the disease, due to the unclear process, qualified medical institutions have been slow to obtain testing qualifications, and a large backlog of suspected patients has brought tremendous pressure to clinical work, but the Disease Control Department because of the short time research and development production test reagent quality "the good and the bad intermingled" , the sample collection standardization is not high question and so on difficult to test the authority to delegate. In this process, the communication and consultation mechanism between the two sides in the early stage is not perfect, affecting the early screening and diagnosis of virus infection, becoming a "Landslide dam" of delayed diagnosis.

Another big problem with nucleic acid testing is the high "false negative" rate, which is only 30% to 50% in confirmed patients. Therefore, the fifth edition of "Diagnosis and Treatment Program" does not require the epidemiological history of suspected cases in Hubei Province, and the lung CT findings as a "clinical diagnosis" category. After the adjustment of diagnostic criteria, on February 12, there was a surge of 14,840 cases of NCP in Hubei, including 13,332 clinically diagnosed cases.

The fifth edition goes back to the original clinical diagnosis. In response, Jiang Qingwu said, "It's important to act decisively. A Emerging Infectious Diseases doesn't have to wait for the pathogen to be clear and a diagnostic method to be established. Fortunately, we now have advanced technology that would have been inconceivable a decade ago. "

Tang Jinling, professor emeritus of epidemiology at the Chinese University of Hong Kong, also pointed out that, like SARS, the news spread in the media made the public and policy makers think, virus isolation and development of detection methods, treatment methods and vaccines are the primary work. "I think this is completely wrong and putting the cart before the horse. These studies are important, but they are too late to control the impending epidemic. "

For example, he said, the last SARS epidemic was not controlled by finding the virus, there is no effective treatment, and the vaccine is still far off. Successful control of SARS ultimately depends on the traditional quarantine, isolation, disinfection, ventilation, personal protection and other health measures. If we had made health and disease control work earlier and more effectively during SARS, it would have spread much less, killed much fewer people, and protected health care workers much better.

A nurse sorts through the belongings of a patient who died of new pneumonia at a hospital in Wuhan, China, on Feb. 24.

"If policymakers lack expertise, the advice of professionals may be in vain. "

On December 31,2019, the first group of experts from the National Health Commission arrived in Wuhan. On that day, Lie group, director of the CDC Emergency Response Center, and his colleagues also arrived in Wuhan, in three groups of 89 patients admitted to Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital were surveyed. Their work includes case surveillance, epidemiological investigations and close contact management. According to the CDC website information, "with a large number of careful investigation and analysis, relevant research and risk assessment reports have been provided to the hands of decision-making departments. "

It is not yet known what the CDC epidemiological findings will be or how these risk assessments will affect decision-making.

On December 26,2019, a team led by virologist Zhang Yongzhen of the CDC and adjunct professor of the Fudan University received a specimen from a patient with fever of unknown origin in Wuhan. On the morning of January 5, they identified a strain of COVID-19 virus in a specimen and sequenced its entire genome. Shanghai Public Health Clinical Center on the same day to the National Health Commission submitted a pathogenic investigation report. The report points out: Since the virus is homologous to the coronavirus causing the SARS epidemic, it should be transmitted through the respiratory tract, and the corresponding prevention and control measures should be taken in public places and antiviral treatment should be used in clinical treatment.

But the report does not seem to have made much difference. From the next day, January 6, to January 10, Wuhan City Health Commission did not report the outbreak. By contrast, as early as January 4, the Hong Kong SAR government set in motion a "serious" response to unexplained pneumonia, even though there were only seven suspected cases.

"It's the public health system, " Zeng told China News Weekly, "It's not that the epidemiological research isn't good, it's not that the virus shouldn't be studied, it's not that the paper shouldn't be published. How are we gonNA get all this information out there in time for containment? The new Crown Disease Prevention and control is not yet an emergency wartime system. It is like war. There is the intelligence department, the General Staff, and the headquarters. The intelligence information goes quickly to the general staff to be studied and judged. After the general staff gives advice, the headquarters immediately makes a decision. It should be such a system."

The success of the SARS epidemic in 2003 was due to the advice of many epidemiologists and disease control experts at the time, recalls public health, Associate Dean of the University of California, Los Angeles, and a senior tenured professor of epidemiology.

However, a disease control expert believes that society still does not draw lessons from the past. During the SARS period, as a prevention and control consultant, he could directly participate in the research and judgment, and the conclusions or recommendations could be quickly translated into prevention and control actions. Now, the provincial CDC findings to the Provincial Health Department report, City, district, county disease control to all levels of Health Commission report, Health Administration Departments to report to the government. "after layers of reporting, efficiency is lost, and the actual information reported may be out of whack. "

Chen Guoqiang and others pointed out that regional decision-makers are the main command of public health events, the need for the first time to organize expert team to provide decision-making recommendations. Wuhan is home to one of the country's most luxurious professional teams in clinical medicine, public health and virus research, and the role of this professional team in the local government's early diagnosis and decision-making process in response to the epidemic does not appear to have been maximized, is something to think about and reflect on.

If policymakers lack expertise, expert advice may also be in vain, Zeng said.

Li Liming stresses that basic public health knowledge and concepts are very important. "How can there be no human-to-human transmission of respiratory infectious diseases? It is only a matter of time. There should be no such thing as 'limited human-to-human transmission. ' If there is some basic consensus in the whole society, this should not be the case for early prevention and control. "

On January 19, Zeng, along with Chinese Academy of Engineering Academician Zhong Nanshan and others, returned to Wuhan as a member of the high level Expert Group of the National Health Commission. On the night of January 20, Zhong Nanshan, speaking live on CCTV, confirmed the existence of human to human transmission in the COVID-19 and said that 14 medical staff had been infected while caring for a patient. Epidemic Prevention and control thus ushered in a turning point.

At a press conference that afternoon, Zeng called publicly for a reduction in the flow of people during the Spring Festival. He would not go to Wuhan if he could, and would not come out if Wuhan could not. "This is not an official call, " he said. "It is a recommendation of our expert group. "

More than a month later, on February 24, bruce Aylward, a senior adviser to the director general of the WHO and head of the COVID-19, said of the measures taken by China, in the face of an unknown new virus, China has taken ambitious, flexible and active prevention and control measures.

When it comes to China's siege tactics, Aylward argues, "these practices are fairly modern in order to quickly find every infected person, track down close contacts and isolate them, " he said. "In a public health emergency like this, people can be mobilized. "

Workers disinfect the closed south China Seafood Market in Wuhan on Feb. 22. Photo / Liberation Daily, Lai Xinlin
